1
00:00:04,855 --> 00:00:06,456
How you guys doing?

2
00:00:06,456 --> 00:00:08,777
Oh, come on, it's the first day of GDC.

3
00:00:08,777 --> 00:00:10,218
You're not drunk yet.

4
00:00:10,218 --> 00:00:12,979
All right.

5
00:00:12,979 --> 00:00:16,721
Hi, my name is Greg Furch.

6
00:00:16,721 --> 00:00:21,904
I'm honored to be here and talk about pre-production.

7
00:00:21,904 --> 00:00:22,824
Like I said, I'm Greg Furch.

8
00:00:22,824 --> 00:00:24,565
So, I've worked on a lot of games.

9
00:00:24,565 --> 00:00:26,526
The talk that I'm going to give

10
00:00:26,526 --> 00:00:29,808
is really focused mainly on XCOM,

11
00:00:29,808 --> 00:00:31,329
Enemy Unknown, and XCOM 2.

12
00:00:34,375 --> 00:00:36,917
and kind of how we approach pre-production for those.

13
00:00:36,917 --> 00:00:37,418
So what is pre-production?

14
00:00:37,418 --> 00:00:40,700
You know, this is a term that we all throw around.

15
00:00:40,700 --> 00:00:45,343
But this is actually the definition of it.

16
00:00:45,343 --> 00:00:49,126
And it doesn't say anything about games, right?

17
00:00:49,126 --> 00:00:51,268
It's a movie term.

18
00:00:51,268 --> 00:00:53,649
But while

19
00:00:55,004 --> 00:00:57,645
We have all the same things that a movie has.

20
00:00:57,645 --> 00:00:59,665
You've gotta figure out your locations

21
00:00:59,665 --> 00:01:01,286
and your characters and your costumes

22
00:01:01,286 --> 00:01:03,406
and casting, all that stuff.

23
00:01:03,406 --> 00:01:05,787
It doesn't have anything about it not being linear.

24
00:01:05,787 --> 00:01:07,287
Doesn't have anything about technology.

25
00:01:07,287 --> 00:01:10,648
All those things that really can kinda crush you.

26
00:01:10,648 --> 00:01:11,308
Or interactivity.

27
00:01:11,308 --> 00:01:17,789
So, something about pre-production that I've found,

28
00:01:17,789 --> 00:01:20,470
everybody I talk to, every AD I talk to,

29
00:01:20,470 --> 00:01:23,871
every studio I talk to, everybody does it different.

30
00:01:25,031 --> 00:01:26,552
And there's a reason for that.

31
00:01:26,552 --> 00:01:28,873
Every game is a little bit different.

32
00:01:28,873 --> 00:01:33,055
The team that's working on the game is a little bit different.

33
00:01:33,055 --> 00:01:37,197
And you've got to cater to those as you're making your game.

34
00:01:37,197 --> 00:01:41,979
So when you read a postmortem about every game,

35
00:01:41,979 --> 00:01:44,320
every time you read one, how many times

36
00:01:44,320 --> 00:01:48,162
have you read postmortems where they say,

37
00:01:48,162 --> 00:01:52,224
the team was tired after coming off the last project?

38
00:01:53,091 --> 00:01:54,853
They don't have the right people on the project early,

39
00:01:54,853 --> 00:01:58,417
because the people that are really, really good

40
00:01:58,417 --> 00:02:01,560
are closing out the project that is finishing.

41
00:02:01,560 --> 00:02:05,704
Not having enough answers or time, right?

42
00:02:05,704 --> 00:02:06,965
Not enough time, not enough money.

43
00:02:06,965 --> 00:02:10,649
And then also not defining your requirements

44
00:02:10,649 --> 00:02:13,712
to exit pre-production and enter production.

45
00:02:15,076 --> 00:02:19,957
And the idea that that's even a hard date is something that is a whole other talk, right?

46
00:02:19,957 --> 00:02:26,119
Whether or not entering production is an actual date that you enter or if it's a staggered

47
00:02:26,119 --> 00:02:26,279
enter.

48
00:02:26,279 --> 00:02:28,419
And I believe it's a staggered enter.

49
00:02:28,419 --> 00:02:31,500
Like characters finish early in the pre-production pipeline.

50
00:02:31,500 --> 00:02:35,461
Environments probably trail behind that a little bit.

51
00:02:37,181 --> 00:02:40,584
UI can trail behind, just like they do

52
00:02:40,584 --> 00:02:42,966
when you're hitting RTM, it's the same kind of thing.

53
00:02:42,966 --> 00:02:47,269
As you're getting closer, they're trailing disciplines,

54
00:02:47,269 --> 00:02:49,351
and the same thing applies for pre-production.

55
00:02:49,351 --> 00:02:50,252
But that's a whole different talk.

56
00:02:50,252 --> 00:02:54,715
So a lot of the mistakes I think that art directors make,

57
00:02:54,715 --> 00:02:59,039
especially new ones, and I know I've done this too,

58
00:03:00,702 --> 00:03:02,743
You know, they don't consider the presentation.

59
00:03:02,743 --> 00:03:05,586
Like, where is the camera going to be for the game?

60
00:03:05,586 --> 00:03:08,128
How is the player going to experience it?

61
00:03:08,128 --> 00:03:12,551
Right, and this is something that I am super passionate about.

62
00:03:12,551 --> 00:03:14,413
Like, I believe this is the key of art direction.

63
00:03:14,413 --> 00:03:16,475
Overestimating pretty pictures.

64
00:03:16,475 --> 00:03:18,977
I think a lot of people get into art direction, right?

65
00:03:18,977 --> 00:03:21,298
And you're like, hey, that's a really pretty picture

66
00:03:21,298 --> 00:03:21,959
up there, isn't it?

67
00:03:22,967 --> 00:03:26,589
It doesn't solve anything for me other than mood.

68
00:03:26,589 --> 00:03:28,311
It doesn't really give me any information.

69
00:03:28,311 --> 00:03:30,872
I can't hand it to a modeler and say make it

70
00:03:30,872 --> 00:03:34,454
because it's still a little too vague, right?

71
00:03:34,454 --> 00:03:37,496
It doesn't abide by any of the presentation rules.

72
00:03:37,496 --> 00:03:40,378
It's a great thing and it's got its place, absolutely.

73
00:03:40,378 --> 00:03:42,840
But I think it's really easy to get enamored

74
00:03:42,840 --> 00:03:46,902
by mood paintings and not ask enough of questions

75
00:03:46,902 --> 00:03:48,483
and misuse your time in pre-production.

76
00:03:49,578 --> 00:03:54,279
So to that end, concepts that pretend to provide answers.

77
00:03:54,279 --> 00:03:56,440
I think everybody's seen these as well.

78
00:03:56,440 --> 00:03:58,840
Like you'll do a picture of a building.

79
00:03:58,840 --> 00:04:00,561
A concept artist will make a building, right?

80
00:04:00,561 --> 00:04:03,181
And they're not thinking about what's the step height,

81
00:04:03,181 --> 00:04:05,002
what are the floor heights?

82
00:04:05,002 --> 00:04:06,182
And every time they make a building,

83
00:04:06,182 --> 00:04:07,843
they make it different, right?

84
00:04:07,843 --> 00:04:09,683
That's not answering any questions.

85
00:04:09,683 --> 00:04:11,244
That's not helping you get forward.

86
00:04:11,244 --> 00:04:12,584
That's not helping you build your pipelines.

87
00:04:12,584 --> 00:04:14,604
It's not helping you establish rules.

88
00:04:14,604 --> 00:04:17,385
And that's the stuff that you need to focus on

89
00:04:17,385 --> 00:04:18,045
in pre-production.

90
00:04:19,799 --> 00:04:22,260
Also focusing on small self-contained items

91
00:04:22,260 --> 00:04:24,420
rather than looking at system work, right?

92
00:04:24,420 --> 00:04:25,741
Like it's great to develop your character

93
00:04:25,741 --> 00:04:27,441
and depending what game you're making,

94
00:04:27,441 --> 00:04:29,162
we make games that are very systems-based.

95
00:04:29,162 --> 00:04:30,862
So like when we look at our characters,

96
00:04:30,862 --> 00:04:32,983
you know, we have isolated ones

97
00:04:32,983 --> 00:04:35,304
and ones that are very heavily reliant on systems.

98
00:04:35,304 --> 00:04:38,405
It's easy to look at them as an example

99
00:04:38,405 --> 00:04:40,285
of just hammering one character,

100
00:04:40,285 --> 00:04:42,346
getting this character perfect.

101
00:04:42,346 --> 00:04:45,367
But by striving for the perfection,

102
00:04:45,367 --> 00:04:47,467
you're not thinking about all the other things

103
00:04:47,467 --> 00:04:49,088
that are gonna eventually affect it, right?

104
00:04:50,842 --> 00:04:54,663
Avoiding difficult gameplay, you know, like not even thinking

105
00:04:54,663 --> 00:04:57,204
about gameplay is something else.

106
00:04:57,204 --> 00:05:00,745
You know, like how is the gameplay going

107
00:05:00,745 --> 00:05:03,346
to actually change how the game is presented

108
00:05:03,346 --> 00:05:05,087
and therefore how my game is arted?

109
00:05:05,087 --> 00:05:08,948
And then this is one recently that's kind

110
00:05:08,948 --> 00:05:11,229
of bugged me a little bit that I've heard about.

111
00:05:11,229 --> 00:05:16,290
Getting pushed to have art bibles in pre-production.

112
00:05:16,290 --> 00:05:17,651
You can't possibly do that.

113
00:05:18,457 --> 00:05:21,178
Right, like somebody can argue with me about it,

114
00:05:21,178 --> 00:05:22,399
but I don't see how you do it.

115
00:05:22,399 --> 00:05:24,159
You can't make an art bible until you're out

116
00:05:24,159 --> 00:05:26,401
of pre-production and entering production.

117
00:05:26,401 --> 00:05:30,022
At the end of pre-production, then you can address this.

118
00:05:30,022 --> 00:05:32,764
But trying to out of the gate figure out, you know,

119
00:05:32,764 --> 00:05:36,286
what your pipelines are and set limits

120
00:05:36,286 --> 00:05:38,667
is, I think, impossible.

121
00:05:38,667 --> 00:05:44,970
So, now that you got a little bit of idea

122
00:05:44,970 --> 00:05:47,111
of where I'm going with this, Enemy Unknown.

123
00:05:47,111 --> 00:05:47,331
So.

124
00:05:48,588 --> 00:05:56,151
Back in 2007 at Firaxis, we had the opportunity to remake XCOM.

125
00:05:56,151 --> 00:05:58,992
Everybody's ever heard of XCOM from 1994, right?

126
00:05:58,992 --> 00:05:59,633
The really old one?

127
00:05:59,633 --> 00:06:03,735
You know, by all accounts, arguably one

128
00:06:03,735 --> 00:06:06,196
of the best strategy games ever made,

129
00:06:06,196 --> 00:06:08,617
one of the best games ever made.

130
00:06:08,617 --> 00:06:11,218
So there's absolutely no pressure, right?

131
00:06:11,218 --> 00:06:14,359
So we had the opportunity to work on this title

132
00:06:14,359 --> 00:06:16,340
and pitch it as something that we wanted to do.

133
00:06:20,313 --> 00:06:27,699
So in 2007, as we started this, we were in a really different place for the studio.

134
00:06:27,699 --> 00:06:30,661
The team was pretty tired.

135
00:06:30,661 --> 00:06:35,685
You know, we had been on probably one of our hardest games that we'd ever worked on, and

136
00:06:35,685 --> 00:06:43,391
we were coming off of that, and we were sliding into the finish on it sideways.

137
00:06:43,391 --> 00:06:45,152
And so everybody was tired.

138
00:06:46,325 --> 00:06:50,545
All the artists were kind of out of steam.

139
00:06:50,545 --> 00:06:54,526
I had actually been, I'd known for probably about eight months

140
00:06:54,526 --> 00:06:57,447
that I was going to, X-Com was going to be mine.

141
00:06:57,447 --> 00:07:02,608
So, while I was kind of helping out on the other project,

142
00:07:02,608 --> 00:07:06,288
I was stealing time and planning, right?

143
00:07:06,288 --> 00:07:08,089
So, I would talk to the designer about half an hour a day

144
00:07:08,089 --> 00:07:11,069
and we'd kind of figure out what we wanted to do and just talk

145
00:07:11,069 --> 00:07:13,250
through what we thought X-Com would be.

146
00:07:15,119 --> 00:07:18,701
That time was invaluable.

147
00:07:18,701 --> 00:07:23,463
I can't say how good that was for me to get my head on straight

148
00:07:23,463 --> 00:07:26,665
and try to filter out all the white noise from everybody

149
00:07:26,665 --> 00:07:28,566
in the studio and everybody around me

150
00:07:28,566 --> 00:07:33,489
that may have hopefully tried to be helpful, made suggestions

151
00:07:33,489 --> 00:07:36,370
about what the game should look like or how it should be.

152
00:07:36,370 --> 00:07:37,891
Because it was just us kind of talking,

153
00:07:37,891 --> 00:07:40,272
didn't really have a lot of that stress.

154
00:07:41,647 --> 00:07:45,369
But when that got done, we had 10 artists and one designer.

155
00:07:45,369 --> 00:07:46,270
We had no programmers.

156
00:07:46,270 --> 00:07:49,311
Programmers were all on fire finishing the other game.

157
00:07:49,311 --> 00:07:52,213
Everybody knows how that works, right?

158
00:07:52,213 --> 00:07:57,696
So we had this opportunity to kind of look at pre-production

159
00:07:57,696 --> 00:07:58,796
from a different perspective.

160
00:07:58,796 --> 00:08:00,117
We'd never gone into pre-production

161
00:08:00,117 --> 00:08:03,159
with just art and a designer, right?

162
00:08:03,159 --> 00:08:06,120
But the important part of that, too, was like we had

163
00:08:06,120 --> 00:08:08,161
to make sure we got the right people on early.

164
00:08:09,342 --> 00:08:12,324
So luckily a lot of the artists had finished

165
00:08:12,324 --> 00:08:16,065
and I was able to get my team together the way I wanted it,

166
00:08:16,065 --> 00:08:20,327
which ironically my team was actually the team I had,

167
00:08:20,327 --> 00:08:23,229
I was art director on Sid Meier's Railroads,

168
00:08:23,229 --> 00:08:24,609
where I actually built this team.

169
00:08:24,609 --> 00:08:28,431
And so that same team now came with me,

170
00:08:28,431 --> 00:08:32,513
so it made it real easy for me to know who I wanted where,

171
00:08:32,513 --> 00:08:33,593
because I had two and a half years, three years

172
00:08:33,593 --> 00:08:34,974
of working with these same people.

173
00:08:39,033 --> 00:08:42,155
But we also didn't have any defined requirements

174
00:08:42,155 --> 00:08:45,437
for how we were going to enter production either.

175
00:08:45,437 --> 00:08:48,279
We had no idea where this was going to take us.

176
00:08:48,279 --> 00:08:49,499
We had a block of time to work with.

177
00:08:49,499 --> 00:08:53,742
And we weren't really sure how that was going to work out.

178
00:08:53,742 --> 00:08:58,785
But on top of that, the biggest thing we had,

179
00:08:58,785 --> 00:08:59,566
we didn't have an engine.

180
00:09:00,312 --> 00:09:02,093
We had no idea what we were gonna make this in.

181
00:09:02,093 --> 00:09:04,814
We had a homebrew engine that was designed

182
00:09:04,814 --> 00:09:06,395
for making Civ games, right?

183
00:09:06,395 --> 00:09:09,256
But we were talking about doing something very different.

184
00:09:09,256 --> 00:09:12,257
And we also didn't have any contemporary games

185
00:09:12,257 --> 00:09:13,098
to compare to.

186
00:09:13,098 --> 00:09:16,739
I mean, the game we were looking at was a game from 1994.

187
00:09:16,739 --> 00:09:19,661
That's a pretty big jump.

188
00:09:19,661 --> 00:09:25,883
And so those are two big issues that really

189
00:09:25,883 --> 00:09:29,345
had us confused about how we wanted to go at first.

190
00:09:31,476 --> 00:09:33,017
So, our approach.

191
00:09:33,017 --> 00:09:37,319
This is one of the earliest screenshots

192
00:09:37,319 --> 00:09:41,060
of us kind of figuring out pre-production.

193
00:09:41,060 --> 00:09:46,023
We decided that we were going to actually make a gameplay simulation.

194
00:09:46,023 --> 00:09:49,985
And so, the first thing I did was I went out

195
00:09:49,985 --> 00:09:52,206
and I made sure I had the right concept people.

196
00:09:52,206 --> 00:09:54,527
Like, I actually went out and found a concept artist.

197
00:09:54,527 --> 00:09:56,908
His work is littered through here, Pierre McGowan.

198
00:09:58,362 --> 00:10:00,444
But, you know, he did an amazing job.

199
00:10:00,444 --> 00:10:03,307
But the thing was we were trying to figure out, like,

200
00:10:03,307 --> 00:10:04,929
you couldn't just put anybody in this job.

201
00:10:04,929 --> 00:10:06,570
The person that filled the concept role

202
00:10:06,570 --> 00:10:08,032
was the heart of your project, right?

203
00:10:08,032 --> 00:10:10,875
So they have to be perfect for what they're doing.

204
00:10:10,875 --> 00:10:13,638
You have to be more selective about the concept artist

205
00:10:13,638 --> 00:10:15,039
than anybody else on the team in that sense.

206
00:10:16,648 --> 00:10:18,589
We wanted to simulate gameplay, right?

207
00:10:18,589 --> 00:10:20,690
Like that was super important to us.

208
00:10:20,690 --> 00:10:22,991
We didn't want this to turn into a sizzle reel.

209
00:10:22,991 --> 00:10:24,592
We didn't want it to turn into a trailer.

210
00:10:24,592 --> 00:10:28,093
And multiple times, there were people

211
00:10:28,093 --> 00:10:29,274
that suggested us going that route.

212
00:10:29,274 --> 00:10:31,214
And so we really held our guns.

213
00:10:31,214 --> 00:10:32,375
We wanted to fake the UI.

214
00:10:32,375 --> 00:10:33,235
We wanted to make it feel

215
00:10:33,235 --> 00:10:36,697
like you were experiencing the game.

216
00:10:36,697 --> 00:10:42,499
And so to that end, we jumped on to using 3D Studio Max.

217
00:10:42,499 --> 00:10:44,840
For us, we were using 3D Studio Max.

218
00:10:46,283 --> 00:10:49,566
Since we didn't have an engine, that was what we knew the most.

219
00:10:49,566 --> 00:10:51,989
And we felt like that gave us the agility

220
00:10:51,989 --> 00:10:54,892
to move around and iterate quickly,

221
00:10:54,892 --> 00:10:57,654
figure out what didn't work fast, get rid of it,

222
00:10:57,654 --> 00:11:00,257
change the cameras, re-render.

223
00:11:00,257 --> 00:11:03,700
It really removed any technology limitations we had.

224
00:11:03,700 --> 00:11:06,764
And the whole idea was, what do we want it to be,

225
00:11:06,764 --> 00:11:08,806
and not how do we work within a box, right?

226
00:11:08,806 --> 00:11:09,667
Other than the gameplay.

227
00:11:11,390 --> 00:11:14,231
And then we questioned everything.

228
00:11:14,231 --> 00:11:17,552
With an XCOM game, why is the camera here?

229
00:11:17,552 --> 00:11:19,874
Is it because that's the best answer,

230
00:11:19,874 --> 00:11:21,474
or because that was the best answer in 1994?

231
00:11:21,474 --> 00:11:27,077
And so we started questioning what was good,

232
00:11:27,077 --> 00:11:28,717
what was bad, deconstructing it.

233
00:11:28,717 --> 00:11:31,419
There were a lot of really good decisions that we kept,

234
00:11:31,419 --> 00:11:33,299
a lot of decisions we thought we could improve on

235
00:11:33,299 --> 00:11:34,700
because technology had advanced so much

236
00:11:34,700 --> 00:11:36,501
in the 17-year gap, or whatever it was.

237
00:11:38,009 --> 00:11:40,050
And then we set project goals.

238
00:11:40,050 --> 00:11:42,310
And this is something that, you know,

239
00:11:42,310 --> 00:11:45,751
when I first did that, I wasn't so sure, right?

240
00:11:45,751 --> 00:11:47,151
Project goals, eh.

241
00:11:47,151 --> 00:11:51,172
They just seemed kinda contrived and weird.

242
00:11:51,172 --> 00:11:53,693
And they weren't tangible things,

243
00:11:53,693 --> 00:11:55,273
typically when I've heard about these things.

244
00:11:55,273 --> 00:11:59,154
And so for us, you know, we set out as a team,

245
00:11:59,154 --> 00:12:00,695
10 artists sitting in a room,

246
00:12:00,695 --> 00:12:02,775
first day that they're in the room,

247
00:12:02,775 --> 00:12:03,395
right on the wall.

248
00:12:04,132 --> 00:12:07,213
We wanted to get best in show at E3.

249
00:12:07,213 --> 00:12:10,494
Not just strategy, we wanted to get best in show.

250
00:12:10,494 --> 00:12:12,895
We wanted to surprise the publisher.

251
00:12:12,895 --> 00:12:13,475
That was another one.

252
00:12:13,475 --> 00:12:16,877
And then we wanted to get game of the year.

253
00:12:16,877 --> 00:12:18,177
Again, not strategy game.

254
00:12:18,177 --> 00:12:21,438
We wanted to go for, take a turn-based strategy game

255
00:12:21,438 --> 00:12:25,040
on consoles, sounds crazy, and get game of the year.

256
00:12:25,040 --> 00:12:27,961
But these were the goals we set out with day one.

257
00:12:27,961 --> 00:12:32,162
So getting to day one, talking about finishing

258
00:12:32,162 --> 00:12:33,103
that other project, right?

259
00:12:34,737 --> 00:12:37,819
This is how a typical development cycle works, right?

260
00:12:37,819 --> 00:12:41,381
You ship the game, and for every up, there's a down.

261
00:12:41,381 --> 00:12:43,823
And that down is the problem.

262
00:12:43,823 --> 00:12:46,785
That down kills you, because re-inflating a team

263
00:12:46,785 --> 00:12:49,706
is so much harder than just maintaining the team.

264
00:12:49,706 --> 00:12:53,729
So again, you start the project, you finish it,

265
00:12:53,729 --> 00:12:55,350
everybody's completely exhausted,

266
00:12:55,350 --> 00:12:57,171
nobody's done laundry, you've got

267
00:12:57,171 --> 00:12:59,553
to repair all your relationship with your family,

268
00:12:59,553 --> 00:13:00,693
call your mom and dad.

269
00:13:01,099 --> 00:13:04,662
I see your wife once in a while.

270
00:13:04,662 --> 00:13:08,284
But so then you've got this bottom out where the project starts, and that's not how you

271
00:13:08,284 --> 00:13:09,825
want to start a project.

272
00:13:09,825 --> 00:13:12,187
For us, this is where we want to be.

273
00:13:12,187 --> 00:13:16,470
So again, I'm kind of loosely helping out on another project as we're doing this, and

274
00:13:16,470 --> 00:13:19,492
I'm thinking about how can I keep my guys from bottoming out?

275
00:13:19,492 --> 00:13:24,635
I want them to day one be excited about what they're doing.

276
00:13:24,635 --> 00:13:25,656
So I started planning for the team.

277
00:13:26,744 --> 00:13:28,944
You know, again, I identified the key positions

278
00:13:28,944 --> 00:13:30,085
and the people that I needed.

279
00:13:30,085 --> 00:13:32,825
I got the 10 guys that I needed to make this thing.

280
00:13:32,825 --> 00:13:33,825
No more, no less.

281
00:13:33,825 --> 00:13:35,686
These are the 10 guys I need.

282
00:13:35,686 --> 00:13:37,246
I needed a concept artist.

283
00:13:37,246 --> 00:13:39,346
I needed a modeler.

284
00:13:39,346 --> 00:13:40,847
I needed a character artist.

285
00:13:40,847 --> 00:13:42,327
I needed a couple animators.

286
00:13:42,327 --> 00:13:45,067
I needed an effects guy, right?

287
00:13:45,067 --> 00:13:46,168
Should have had a tech artist,

288
00:13:46,168 --> 00:13:48,728
but we didn't have one at the time.

289
00:13:48,728 --> 00:13:53,069
But, so we went after those people that we needed.

290
00:13:53,069 --> 00:13:53,989
We made sure I had them.

291
00:13:54,962 --> 00:13:57,565
I collected concepts in that eight-month period, right?

292
00:13:57,565 --> 00:13:58,606
I was constantly working.

293
00:13:58,606 --> 00:14:02,029
I went and got an outsource budget.

294
00:14:02,029 --> 00:14:04,151
Let me go start collecting concepts.

295
00:14:04,151 --> 00:14:08,795
I actually hired our concept guy as a contractor.

296
00:14:09,935 --> 00:14:12,657
before I could get a position approved for him in the studio.

297
00:14:12,657 --> 00:14:14,218
So I was paying him to make concepts,

298
00:14:14,218 --> 00:14:15,979
and I was outsourcing to another guy

299
00:14:15,979 --> 00:14:18,440
just so I could get my feet on the ground

300
00:14:18,440 --> 00:14:19,821
before the team hit the ground.

301
00:14:19,821 --> 00:14:21,482
I don't know if anybody's had that problem

302
00:14:21,482 --> 00:14:23,404
where your team just starts the day that you start,

303
00:14:23,404 --> 00:14:26,246
and it's like, hey, go make pre-production, right?

304
00:14:26,246 --> 00:14:30,368
I'm betting a lot of people have had that, right?

305
00:14:30,368 --> 00:14:31,849
Somebody, not just me, come on.

306
00:14:33,487 --> 00:14:37,009
So I was consciously building my team, right,

307
00:14:37,009 --> 00:14:37,990
in this whole process.

308
00:14:37,990 --> 00:14:40,592
One of the more controversial things I did

309
00:14:40,592 --> 00:14:42,694
was actually isolated my team in a room.

310
00:14:42,694 --> 00:14:45,376
I booked a conference room.

311
00:14:45,376 --> 00:14:50,700
I went out and got brand new computers for everybody.

312
00:14:50,700 --> 00:14:52,802
They walked in, day one, everybody

313
00:14:52,802 --> 00:14:56,765
had a new computer with a concept, ready to go.

314
00:14:56,765 --> 00:14:59,987
And that was super important.

315
00:14:59,987 --> 00:15:00,908
It was a fresh start.

316
00:15:01,939 --> 00:15:08,981
By isolating the guys in a room, there were so many reasons to do that from a management

317
00:15:08,981 --> 00:15:09,601
level, right?

318
00:15:09,601 --> 00:15:13,423
Like, you know, I had 10 artists, I had no programmers.

319
00:15:13,423 --> 00:15:16,484
I wanted these guys to believe that they can make anything.

320
00:15:16,484 --> 00:15:18,004
I wanted to empower them.

321
00:15:18,004 --> 00:15:21,985
It created a little bit of a mystique to the team because I kept everyone out.

322
00:15:21,985 --> 00:15:25,527
Not only were they in that room together, no one saw what we were working on.

323
00:15:26,553 --> 00:15:29,254
And it's crazy, and it wasn't me trying to be a jerk.

324
00:15:29,254 --> 00:15:32,735
It was me, I needed to filter out the white noise, right?

325
00:15:32,735 --> 00:15:36,656
I didn't want anybody, you know, critiquing a sectoid

326
00:15:36,656 --> 00:15:40,197
before I had figured out what a soldier looked like too

327
00:15:40,197 --> 00:15:41,197
and what the terrain looked like.

328
00:15:41,197 --> 00:15:43,618
And I just didn't want that.

329
00:15:43,618 --> 00:15:46,358
And then on top of it, I didn't want anybody

330
00:15:46,358 --> 00:15:49,099
also kind of hammering my team on it either

331
00:15:49,099 --> 00:15:49,779
when I'm not around.

332
00:15:49,779 --> 00:15:52,120
And not that anybody do that.

333
00:15:53,141 --> 00:15:54,622
It just happens in development.

334
00:15:54,622 --> 00:15:57,485
Everybody wants to be part of it, so people start talking.

335
00:15:57,485 --> 00:15:58,526
So we kind of filtered that out.

336
00:15:58,526 --> 00:15:59,687
And then the biggest thing, though,

337
00:15:59,687 --> 00:16:05,252
was I used the rest of the studio as my litmus test

338
00:16:05,252 --> 00:16:07,174
for whether or not this game was going to be cool.

339
00:16:07,174 --> 00:16:09,897
When they saw it, it was going to be the first time

340
00:16:09,897 --> 00:16:10,897
anybody had seen it.

341
00:16:10,897 --> 00:16:12,859
And that was a huge role for us.

342
00:16:12,859 --> 00:16:15,702
They played a significant part in the process.

343
00:16:17,797 --> 00:16:21,660
And then the other thing about being in the room together was that it established this

344
00:16:21,660 --> 00:16:22,200
critique tone.

345
00:16:22,200 --> 00:16:26,183
Like we had guys that were super extroverted and guys that were super introverted and they

346
00:16:26,183 --> 00:16:27,324
were sitting right next to each other.

347
00:16:27,324 --> 00:16:34,290
And over a period of the four months that we worked on this, because day one to end

348
00:16:34,290 --> 00:16:35,070
was four months.

349
00:16:38,144 --> 00:16:39,605
you watch the guys who were introverted

350
00:16:39,605 --> 00:16:40,946
just kind of start coming out of their shell,

351
00:16:40,946 --> 00:16:43,087
and they'd start talking about their work.

352
00:16:43,087 --> 00:16:47,369
And the honesty in the discussion about what the work was,

353
00:16:47,369 --> 00:16:49,470
A, they all felt empowered to talk to each other

354
00:16:49,470 --> 00:16:51,571
about their work, because they were all in a room together,

355
00:16:51,571 --> 00:16:53,252
they couldn't avoid it.

356
00:16:53,252 --> 00:16:57,214
But you also started to see the team chemistry change,

357
00:16:57,214 --> 00:16:59,315
that guys who were in individual offices before

358
00:16:59,315 --> 00:17:00,796
and would just hide in there.

359
00:17:01,790 --> 00:17:02,950
were now unable to do that.

360
00:17:02,950 --> 00:17:05,411
And so they were communicating back and forth

361
00:17:05,411 --> 00:17:08,072
in a way that was completely new.

362
00:17:08,072 --> 00:17:10,913
You read all that stuff about in management books

363
00:17:10,913 --> 00:17:14,294
about level four communication, right?

364
00:17:14,294 --> 00:17:15,134
Like honesty.

365
00:17:15,134 --> 00:17:16,194
We truly achieved that.

366
00:17:16,194 --> 00:17:18,955
Like these guys had no problem talking to each other

367
00:17:18,955 --> 00:17:20,256
about what was right and wrong.

368
00:17:20,256 --> 00:17:23,137
And that was enormous when starting a project.

369
00:17:23,137 --> 00:17:26,558
And so that feeds into achieving buy-in.

370
00:17:26,558 --> 00:17:28,658
They all felt empowered, right?

371
00:17:28,658 --> 00:17:29,739
Everybody could affect change.

372
00:17:32,846 --> 00:17:35,947
And on top of that, I was trying to provide concepts

373
00:17:35,947 --> 00:17:38,367
that challenged their skills, challenged

374
00:17:38,367 --> 00:17:40,048
them to step to the next level.

375
00:17:40,048 --> 00:17:42,048
And every time I did it, they met it and crushed it.

376
00:17:42,048 --> 00:17:45,369
The achieving buy-in is the easy part.

377
00:17:45,369 --> 00:17:48,450
The maintaining buy-in is the hard part, right?

378
00:17:48,450 --> 00:17:50,311
And this is what gets hard about making games.

379
00:17:50,311 --> 00:17:51,871
But even during pre-production, you

380
00:17:51,871 --> 00:17:54,372
had to find these little points to kind of buoy the team,

381
00:17:54,372 --> 00:17:57,492
keep them believing in what you're doing.

382
00:17:57,492 --> 00:17:59,133
Because if any one guy in this process,

383
00:17:59,133 --> 00:18:00,933
as I've thought about this now.

384
00:18:01,860 --> 00:18:05,084
you know, 10 years of looking back on it.

385
00:18:05,084 --> 00:18:07,347
If any one guy in this group of people in that room

386
00:18:07,347 --> 00:18:10,570
doesn't believe in what I'm doing, it doesn't happen.

387
00:18:10,570 --> 00:18:11,431
So this is the room, believe it or not.

388
00:18:11,431 --> 00:18:17,278
And this is one of those kind of buoying moments.

389
00:18:17,278 --> 00:18:19,801
We were actually, if you notice,

390
00:18:19,801 --> 00:18:22,124
there's old Xcom in the background.

391
00:18:22,672 --> 00:18:26,335
the original game, and guys are learning about the game they're playing,

392
00:18:26,335 --> 00:18:30,118
because we're remaking, because again, a lot of these guys never played it,

393
00:18:30,118 --> 00:18:32,359
because they were too young.

394
00:18:32,359 --> 00:18:37,924
And so we're learning about the old game while we're making the new game,

395
00:18:37,924 --> 00:18:39,865
and trying to make sure that was fresh in everybody's mind.

396
00:18:39,865 --> 00:18:43,709
And you can see the designers in there.

397
00:18:43,709 --> 00:18:46,231
He's standing there, you know, looking at what the guys are doing,

398
00:18:46,231 --> 00:18:50,454
talking to them about how the game works, which was a great experience.

399
00:18:50,454 --> 00:18:51,995
That room got so hot, it was ridiculous.

400
00:18:53,131 --> 00:18:56,712
There was no air conditioning and it was winter

401
00:18:56,712 --> 00:18:59,273
and all those computers and monitors, it was ridiculous.

402
00:18:59,273 --> 00:19:03,115
So some of the questions that we had,

403
00:19:03,115 --> 00:19:04,775
you know, what was the theme of the game?

404
00:19:04,775 --> 00:19:06,456
What's the setting of the game?

405
00:19:06,456 --> 00:19:08,957
How do we, what are design goals?

406
00:19:08,957 --> 00:19:09,897
How do those affect art?

407
00:19:09,897 --> 00:19:11,358
You know, where is the camera?

408
00:19:11,358 --> 00:19:12,498
What do we have to communicate?

409
00:19:12,498 --> 00:19:17,000
Where is all that stuff gonna be?

410
00:19:17,000 --> 00:19:18,380
What is important to the designer?

411
00:19:19,372 --> 00:19:21,013
And then what are the visual opportunities?

412
00:19:21,013 --> 00:19:22,234
Again, can we drop a camera down?

413
00:19:22,234 --> 00:19:23,535
Can we create immersion points?

414
00:19:23,535 --> 00:19:26,018
Can you even push those further?

415
00:19:26,018 --> 00:19:27,159
Do they interrupt the gameplay?

416
00:19:27,159 --> 00:19:28,720
How fast do they have to be?

417
00:19:28,720 --> 00:19:33,345
We were able to change these things on the fly.

418
00:19:33,345 --> 00:19:37,248
If the run cycle was too long, speed it up.

419
00:19:37,248 --> 00:19:39,570
Because we're working in a platform

420
00:19:39,570 --> 00:19:40,852
that was very easy for us.

421
00:19:42,406 --> 00:19:45,067
And then setting up our pipelines, working large to small.

422
00:19:45,067 --> 00:19:47,147
What's your largest creature?

423
00:19:47,147 --> 00:19:48,927
What's your smallest creature?

424
00:19:48,927 --> 00:19:49,968
Make sure you include them,

425
00:19:49,968 --> 00:19:53,548
because they're your bookends.

426
00:19:53,548 --> 00:19:55,069
And then looking at the terrain,

427
00:19:55,069 --> 00:19:57,129
looking at the buildings, working in,

428
00:19:57,129 --> 00:19:59,870
asking the right questions about what's important,

429
00:19:59,870 --> 00:20:01,010
what's gonna need to be solved,

430
00:20:01,010 --> 00:20:02,050
and attacking it from that perspective.

431
00:20:02,050 --> 00:20:03,791
So our first answers.

432
00:20:03,791 --> 00:20:06,511
This is the first concept from XCOM.

433
00:20:07,380 --> 00:20:09,581
Again, we're trying to establish our mood.

434
00:20:09,581 --> 00:20:11,602
We're trying to figure out what's the tone of this game.

435
00:20:11,602 --> 00:20:14,864
Again, we wanted to use a lot of things

436
00:20:14,864 --> 00:20:17,145
that had a context to people.

437
00:20:17,145 --> 00:20:18,426
But then we wanted to give them a twist.

438
00:20:18,426 --> 00:20:20,307
And so you can see this farmhouse

439
00:20:20,307 --> 00:20:21,308
is recognizable to everyone, right?

440
00:20:21,308 --> 00:20:22,809
Resonates with everybody.

441
00:20:22,809 --> 00:20:25,050
But you've got these weird soldiers in the foreground

442
00:20:25,050 --> 00:20:26,931
and you've got this crazy orange and greenish light

443
00:20:26,931 --> 00:20:30,713
in the background coming out of one of the windows.

444
00:20:30,713 --> 00:20:32,754
We wanted to have that unsettling kind of feel.

445
00:20:32,754 --> 00:20:35,436
This was also, we did two of these and we moved on.

446
00:20:36,625 --> 00:20:38,347
Right? And this is before I had the team.

447
00:20:38,347 --> 00:20:39,869
We had two of them, moved on.

448
00:20:39,869 --> 00:20:41,812
This is the little gray.

449
00:20:41,812 --> 00:20:42,573
This is sectoid.

450
00:20:42,573 --> 00:20:45,556
Everybody knows what one of these looks like,

451
00:20:45,556 --> 00:20:47,559
but redesigning one is actually kind of hard.

452
00:20:47,559 --> 00:20:50,582
Because everybody does know what they look like.

453
00:20:50,582 --> 00:20:52,324
So doing a new take on it was tough.

454
00:20:53,011 --> 00:20:54,752
But this is our smallest character in the game.

455
00:20:54,752 --> 00:20:56,433
And this is our largest.

456
00:20:56,433 --> 00:20:57,573
This was the sectopod.

457
00:20:57,573 --> 00:21:00,735
This is the early incarnation of it.

458
00:21:00,735 --> 00:21:03,737
He's 30 feet tall, the sectoid is four.

459
00:21:03,737 --> 00:21:05,358
And we had to get them both on the screen.

460
00:21:05,358 --> 00:21:07,599
I remember us sliding them around at max.

461
00:21:07,599 --> 00:21:09,460
Can you still play the game with the designer?

462
00:21:09,460 --> 00:21:11,041
Can you still play the game from this perspective?

463
00:21:13,088 --> 00:21:15,450
And from there, we had started attacking the presentation.

464
00:21:15,450 --> 00:21:17,232
Like I was saying, where is the camera?

465
00:21:17,232 --> 00:21:18,453
Can you play the game from here?

466
00:21:18,453 --> 00:21:20,255
We looked at all these little vignettes

467
00:21:20,255 --> 00:21:21,817
and then started moving the camera around.

468
00:21:21,817 --> 00:21:23,118
What happens when you go in buildings?

469
00:21:23,118 --> 00:21:24,820
Does it get, does the camera push in?

470
00:21:24,820 --> 00:21:26,922
Does it get more claustrophobic?

471
00:21:26,922 --> 00:21:29,385
Can we pitch the camera a little differently?

472
00:21:29,385 --> 00:21:32,608
This little study of nine drawings was huge for us.

473
00:21:32,608 --> 00:21:35,251
And then we took that and we translated it.

474
00:21:35,924 --> 00:21:39,767
Right? This is actually built to standards that we were going

475
00:21:39,767 --> 00:21:41,369
to model with, like we were trying to figure

476
00:21:41,369 --> 00:21:42,189
out what those were.

477
00:21:42,189 --> 00:21:44,631
And then we sent it back into concept to,

478
00:21:44,631 --> 00:21:47,013
this is our farmhouse, hit it.

479
00:21:47,013 --> 00:21:47,974
How does this work?

480
00:21:47,974 --> 00:21:51,677
So, like I said about the little room we're in,

481
00:21:51,677 --> 00:21:53,139
this is the first day.

482
00:21:53,139 --> 00:21:56,321
You can see the date on the wall.

